                  I dont see how it maters for raid, if aggro reduction is built in or if it comes from the outside. Forget is not an option, I agree. I know that for EQ2, aggro was a constraint for caster. I did not guess the 70% but not my area of expertise, I just take what you say.<br />
<br />
With the lvl range I reached, Druid snare and/or root broke on damage (I think it also has cast time), Psi snare is less %, Nekro fear is unreached for solo play but snare is also less %.<br />
<br />
Ok, I stop twisting but I really thought, what you are writing was not consistent.<br />
We have a defensive barrier, I think anymore than that is not required. Sorcerer is not a defensive class, if there is work spend on the class why not extend on areas I feel more rewarding (spell ID, spell counter).<br />
<br />
If you like to gain time with snare after catching aggro the snare needs to be already on the mob. When there is a proc percentage (and the duration is not overlapping) I think you will be dead in the most cases independent from if you use a defensive barrier or not (then why use defensive in the first place). I guess high content mob will be snare/root immune in the future. No gain in that cases either. Aggro reduction in a self buff is a cheap way in my opinion but you would need it in an offensive barrier, defensive you will generate less aggro anyway.<br />
<br />
All that percentage things would mean you would be gambling all the time (oops, proced  survive; oops, didnt proc  dead). Currently the mechanic how the barrier, ward, snare, root works are predictable (except barrier stun and star root, and thats why I dont reliant on them). This is one of the important points why I think Sorcerer has a good class design.<br />
<br />
I asked a Bard: Bard proc is self only melee (at least until lvl 38)
                  
